l cycle in response to hormonal stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is correct with regards to endometrial hyperplasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Progesterone therapy prevents its progression","Oestrogen suppresses its development","Simple hyperplasia has a high risk of malignant transformation","Complex hyperplasia without atypia rarely requires treatment","Atypical hyperplasia has minimal association with endometrial cancer"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEndometrial hyperplasia represents abnormal proliferation of the endometrial glands. \u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is actually a primary treatment for endometrial hyperplasia, as it counteracts the effects of unopposed oestrogen. \u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen\u003C/strong\u003E stimulation without progesterone opposition is the main driver of endometrial hyperplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E has approximately 1% risk of progression to cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EComplex hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E requires treatment due to its higher risk of progression. \u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E has up to 30% risk of concurrent endometrial cancer and requires prompt management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EObesity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOestrogen-only hormone replacement therapy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETamoxifen therapy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endometrial hyperplasia is caused by unopposed oestrogen stimulation of the endometrium","Progesterone therapy is a key treatment for endometrial hyperplasia","Endometrial hyperplasia is a precursor lesion to endometrial carcinoma"],"references":["Sanderson PA, Critchley HO, Williams AR, Arends MJ, Saunders PT. New concepts for an old problem: the diagnosis of endometrial hyperplasia. Hum Reprod Update. 2017 Mar 1;23(2):232-254. doi: 10.1093/humupd/dmw042. PMID: 27920066; PMCID: PMC5850217.","Singh G, Cue L, Puckett Y. Endometrial Hyperplasia. 2024 Apr 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809528.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56995"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56995"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:40:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:43:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8398"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71486"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":nu